//! TODO-3 binding-proof fixture from a Samsung Galaxy S20+ 5G (SM-G986U,
//! Snapdragon 865, Android 13 / API 33, One UI 5.1, Knox 3.9). Captured
//! on 2026-04-17 via dotwave's three-key ceremony (cert EC + attest EC +
//! HMAC with operational binding proof).
//!
//! Contains everything the pallet-side parser needs to verify a TODO 3
//! attestation payload end-to-end:
//!
//! - `CHALLENGE_HEX` — 32-byte attestation challenge passed to
//!   `setAttestationChallenge` on all three key generations. Both
//!   attestation chains embed this into their KeyDescription extension;
//!   the pallet verifies byte-exact round-trip.
//!
//! - `CERT_EC_LEAF_HEX` — leaf cert of the user's P-256 cert signing key
//!   (`zkpki_cert_ec`). KeyDescription has the attested pubkey + security
//!   level + RootOfTrust (deviceLocked=true, verifiedBootState=Verified).
//!
//! - `CERT_EC_INT1_HEX`, `CERT_EC_INT2_HEX`, `CERT_EC_ROOT_HEX` — the two
//!   intermediates and the Google Hardware Attestation Root CA. These
//!   are byte-identical to the intermediates/root in the attest_ec chain
//!   because the device provisioned them at manufacture time and they're
//!   shared across every attestation request on this device.
//!
//! - `ATTEST_EC_LEAF_HEX` — leaf cert of the dedicated binding-proof key
//!   (`zkpki_attest_ec`). Different pubkey from the cert_ec leaf, same
//!   attestation challenge, same RootOfTrust, same root CA. It's the
//!   pubkey on this cert that the pallet uses to verify the binding
//!   signature.
//!
//! - `HMAC_BINDING_OUTPUT_HEX` — the HMAC-SHA256 output over the fixed
//!   context string `"zkpki-binding-proof-v1"`, computed inside StrongBox
//!   using the HMAC key (which has no attestation chain on Samsung Knox,
//!   per Kotlin ceremony comments).
//!
//! - `BINDING_SIGNATURE_HEX` — DER-encoded ECDSA-SHA256 signature produced
//!   by `zkpki_attest_ec` over the commitment:
//!     `blake2b_256(HMAC_BINDING_OUTPUT || CHALLENGE)`.
//!
//! - `EXPECTED_COMMITMENT` — the 32-byte Blake2b-256 of
//!   (hmac_output || challenge). Recorded for test assertion so the
//!   parser's commitment computation can be verified against a
//!   ground-truth value, not just "signature verifies" which would also
//!   pass if the parser accidentally hashed the wrong thing.

